This article is a presidential proclamation from December 5, 2013, declaring December 7 as National Pearl Harbor Remembrance Day. The proclamation honors the men and women who sacrificed their lives during the attack on Pearl Harbor and acknowledges those who fought in World War II. It also recognizes the efforts of those on the home front and emphasizes the resilience and strength of the American people. The proclamation encourages Americans to observe the day with appropriate ceremonies and activities, and calls for the flag of the United States to be flown at half-staff in honor of those who died at Pearl Harbor.